DIV1.P:
THERE is another sort of Antithesis, the beauty of which consists, in surprising us by


the unexpected contrasts of things which it brings together. Much wit may be shewn in this; but it belongs wholly to pieces of professed wit and humour, and can find no place in grave compositions. Mr. Pope, who is remarkably fond of Antithesis, is often happy in this use of the figure. So, in his Rape of the Lock:
Whether the nymph shall break Diana's law,

Or some frail china jar receive a flaw;

Or stain her honour, or her new brocade;

Forget her prayers, or miss a masquerade;

Or lose her heart, or necklace, at a ball,

Or whether heaven has doomed that Shock must fall. What is called the point of an epigram, con∣sists, for most part, in some Antithesis of this kind; surprising us with the smart and un∣expected turn, which it gives to the thought; and in the fewer words it is brought out, it is always the happier.
